  },
  [
    "h1",
    {},
    "Introduction to Verbs"
  ],
  [
    "p",
    {},
    [
      "In Ancient and Modern Greek, verbs are the heartbeat of the sentence. Most regular verbs follow predictable patterns. Explore the ",
      [
        "strong",
        {},
        "Present Indicative Active"
      ],
      " below."
    ]
  ],
  [
    "h2",
    {},
    "The Anatomy of a Greek Verb"
  ],
  [
    "p",
    {},
    [
      "Greek verbs have a ",
      [
        "strong",
        {},
        "stem"
      ],
      " and an ",
      [
        "strong",
        {},
        "ending"
      ],
      ". The stem carries the meaning (e.g., ",
      [
        "em",
        {},
        "λύ-"
      ],
      " means \"loose\"), while the ending tells us who is performing the action."
    ]
  ],
  [
    "ul",
    {
      "className": "phrase-list"
    },
    [
      "li",
      {},
      [
        "span",
        {
          "className": "spanish"
        },
        [
          [
            "strong",
            {},
            "-ω"
          ],
          ": 1st Person Singular"
        ]
      ],
      [
        "span",
        {
          "className": "meaning"
        },
        "I"
      ]
    ],
    [
      "li",
      {},
      [
        "span",
        {
          "className": "spanish"
        },
        [
          [
            "strong",
            {},
            "-εις"
          ],
          ": 2nd Person Singular"
        ]
      ],
      [
        "span",
        {
          "className": "meaning"
        },
        "You"
      ]
    ],
    [
      "li",
      {},
      [
        "span",
        {
          "className": "spanish"
        },
        [
          [
            "strong",
            {},
            "-ει"
          ],
          ": 3rd Person Singular"
        ]
      ],
      [
        "span",
        {
          "className": "meaning"
        },
        "He/She/It"
      ]
    ]
  ]
